1978: [[Aleksandr Solzhenitsyn]], [[Nobel Prize]]-winning novelist (\"A World Split Apart\" [https://www.americanrhetoric.com/speeches/alexandersolzhenitsynharvard.htm video; audio; text])\n* 1977: [[Barbara Jordan]], [[US Representative]] representing Texas ([http://texashistory.unt.edu/ark:/67531/metapth611163/m1/3/ text])\n* 1976: [[Daniel Patrick Moynihan]], US senator representing New York\n* 1975: [[Archibald Cox]], [[Harvard Law School]] Professor of Law\n* 1974: [[Ralph Ellison]], novelist\n* 1973: Rev. [[Theodore Hesburgh]], President of the [[University of Notre Dame]]\n* 1972: [[Roy Jenkins]], former Deputy Leader of the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]]\n* 1971: [[Alan Paton]], South African novelist\n* 1970: [[Antonio Carrillo Flores]], former [[Secretary of Foreign Affairs (Mexico)|Mexican Secretary of Foreign Affairs]]\n* 1969: [[Jean Rey (politician)|Jean Rey]], Belgian politician and 2nd [[President of the European Commission]]\n* 1969: [[Stewart Udall]], 37th [[United States Secretary of the Interior]]\n* 1968: [[Mohammad Reza Pahlavi]], [[Shah of Iran]] ([http://harvardmag.com/media/1968_Pahlavi.pdf excerpts])\n* 1967: [[Edwin O. Reischauer]], diplomat and Harvard professor\n* 1966: [[W. Averell Harriman]], businessman, politician, and diplomat\n* 1965: [[Adlai Stevenson II]], 31st [[Governor of Illinois]] and 5th [[United States Ambassador to the United Nations]]\n* 1964: [[Alberto Lleras Camargo]], 20th [[President of Colombia]]\n* 1963: [[U Thant]], 3rd [[Secretary-General of the United Nations]]\n* 1962: [[William McChesney Martin]], 9th [[Chair of the Federal Reserve|Chairman of the Federal Reserve]] ([https://fraser.stlouisfed.org/title/448/item/7860 text])\n* 1962: [[Lionel Trilling]], Professor of English, [[Columbia University]]\n* 1961: [[Alec Douglas-Home]], [[Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs|Secretary of State for Foreign Affairs]], United Kingdom\n* 1961: [[F. Cyril James]], Vice Chancellor, [[McGill University]]\n* 1960: [[Robert Menzies]], 12th [[Prime Minister of Australia]]\n* 1960: [[Paul-Henri Spaak]], 2nd [[Secretary General of NATO]]\n* 1959: [[Pieter Geyl]], Dutch historian and [[Utrecht University]] professor\n* 1959: [[C. Douglas Dillon]], 21st [[United States Under Secretary of State]]\n* 1958: [[Neil H. McElroy]], 6th [[United States Secretary of Defense]]\n* 1958: [[Raymond Aron]], French historian and journalist\n* 1957: [[Erwin Panofsky]], art historian\n* 1957: Lady [[Barbara Jackson (author)|Barbara Jackson]], British author\n* 1956: [[Herbert Butterfield]], British historian and [[University of Cambridge]] professor\n* 1956: [[John F. Kennedy]], US senator representing Massachusetts ([http://www.jfklibrary.org/Asset-Viewer/Archives/JFKPOF-135-016.aspx text])\n* 1955: [[Luis Mu\u00f1oz Mar\u00edn]], Puerto Rican poet, journalist, and politician\n* 1955: [[Konrad Adenauer]], [[Chancellor of Germany|Chancellor of the Federal Republic of Germany]]\n* 1954: [[Henry Cabot Lodge]], former US senator representing Massachusetts\n* 1954: [[Robert Schuman]], former [[Prime Minister of France]]\n* 1954: [[Grayson L. Kirk]], political scientist and 14th [[President of Columbia University]]\n* 1953: [[John P. Marquand]], [[Pulitzer Prize]]-winning novelist\n* 1953: [[Lester B. Pearson]], Canadian statesman and historian\n* 1952: [[John Foster Dulles]], US senator representing New York\n* 1952: [[Joseph S. Clark Jr.]], lawyer and politician\n* 1951: [[Thornton Wilder]], playwright and novelist\n* 1951: [[Warren Austin]], US senator representing Vermont, 2nd [[United States Ambassador to the United Nations]]\n* 1951: [[Charles Edward Wilson (General Electric executive)|Charles Edward Wilson]], President of [[General Electric]]\n* 1950: [[Dean Acheson]], statesman and lawyer\n* 1950: [[Ralph Flanders]], US senator representing Vermont\n* 1950: [[Carlos P. Romulo]], Filipino [[Secretary of Foreign Affairs (Philippines)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]]\n* 1949: [[Ralph Bunche]], political scientist\n* 1949: [[Lucius D. Clay, Jr.]], General of the [[United States Army]]\n* 1949: Sir [[Oliver Franks, Baron Franks]], Ambassador of the United Kingdom to the United Nations\n* 1948: [[Trygve Lie]], 1st [[Secretary-General of the United Nations]]\n* 1947: [[George Marshall]], 50th [[United States Secretary of State]] (\"What Must Be Done?\" [http://www.humanity.org/voices/commencements/george-marshall-harvard-university-speech-1947 text])\n* 1946: [[Maurice J. Tobin]], 6th [[United States Secretary of Labor]]\n* 1945: [[C. D. Howe]], Canadian [[Department of Munitions and Supply|Minister of Munitions and Supply]]\n* 1945: Sir [[Alexander Fleming]], Scottish scientist\n* 1945: [[Ernest King]], Fleet Admiral, [[United States Navy]]\n* 1944: [[Walter Lippmann]], journalist\n* 1943: [[Joseph Grew]], 13th [[United States Ambassador to Japan]]\n* 1943: [[Winston Churchill]], [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]]\n* 1942: [[Henry L. Stimson]], 45th [[United States Secretary of War]]\n* 1942: [[Frederick Paul Keppel]], former President of [[Carnegie Corporation of New York]]\n* 1942: [[Raymond Gram Swing]], journalist\n* 1942: [[Frank Knox]], 47th [[United States Secretary of the Navy]]\n* 1941: [[Edward Wood, 3rd Viscount Halifax]], [[List of ambassadors of the United Kingdom to the United States|Ambassador of the United Kingdom to the United States]]\n* 1941: [[Clarence Addison Dykstra]], Chairman of the National Defense Board\n* 1941: [[Vannevar Bush]], National Defense Research Committee\n* 1940: [[Robert Gordon Sproul|Robert Sproul]], 11th President of the [[University of California]]\n* 1940: [[Carl Sandburg]], author and poet\n* 1940: [[Cordell Hull]], 47th [[United States Secretary of State]]\n* 1938: [[John Buchan, 1st Baron Tweedsmuir]], Scottish novelist and historian, 15th [[Governor General of Canada]]\n* 1934: [[Harold W. Dodds]], 15th [[President of Princeton University]]\n* 1934: [[Charles F. Martin]], President of [[McGill University]]\n* 1933: Sir [[Ronald Lindsay]], British civil servant and diplomat\n* 1931: Sir [[Arthur Salter, 1st Baron Salter|James Salter]], author and political scientist\n* 1929: [[Ernest Barker]], political scientist\n* 1927: [[Josiah Stamp, 1st Baron Stamp]], British civil servant\n* 1926: [[Arthur Currie]], General of the Canadian Corps\n* 1924: [[Owen D. Young]], businessman, [[Dawes Commission]]\n* 1923: [[William Lyon Mackenzie King]], Canadian politician\n* 1918: [[Rufus Isaacs, 1st Marquess of Reading|Rufus Isaacs, 1st Earl of Reading]], British politician\n* 1917: [[Cecil Spring Rice]], [[List of ambassadors of the United Kingdom to the United States|Ambassador of the United Kingdom to the United States of America]]\n* 1914: [[David F. Houston]], 5th [[United States Secretary of Agriculture]]\n* 1914: Sir [[Charles Fitzpatrick]], 5th [[Chief Justice of Canada]]\n* 1910: [[George Walter Prothero]], British writer and historian\n* 1909: Sir [[Napier Shaw]], British meteorologist\n* 1907: [[James Bryce, 1st Viscount Bryce|James Bryce]], British historian, statesman, and diplomat ([http://cambridge.dlconsulting.com/cgi-bin/cambridge?a=d&d=Tribune19070803-01.2.20# excerpts])\n* 1904: [[Henry Cabot Lodge]], US senator representing Massachusetts\n* 1904: Baron [[Kaneko Kentar\u014d]], Japanese envoy to the United States\n* 1904: [[William Osler]], Canadian physician\n* 1900: [[Julian Pauncefote, 1st Baron Pauncefote]], British diplomat\n* 1898: [[John Campbell-Gordon, 7th Earl of Aberdeen]], British politician\n* 1890: [[Leslie Stephen]], British author and literary critic\n* 1886: [[Lyon Playfair, 1st Baron Playfair]], British politician\n* 1884: [[Richard Claverhouse Jebb]], British classical scholar and politician\n* 1878: [[Frederick Hamilton-Temple-Blackwood, 1st Marquess of Dufferin and Ava]], British politician\n* 1875: [[Thomas Carlyle]], Scottish essayist and historian\n* 1871: [[George Robinson, 1st Marquess of Ripon]], British politician\n* 1862: [[John Stuart Mill]], British philosopher and economist\n* 1860: [[Richard Lyons, 1st Viscount Lyons]], British diplomat\n* 1858: [[Francis Napier, 10th Lord Napier|Francis Napier, 1st Baron Ettrick]], British diplomat\n* 1853: [[James Bruce, 8th Earl of Elgin]], British colonial administrator and diplomat\n* 1846: [[Thomas Grenville]], British politician\n* 1844: [[Charles Lyell]], British lawyer and geologist\n* 1831: [[Richard Whately]], British rhetorician, logician, economist, and theologian\n}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Academic regalia of Harvard University]]\n* [[History of Harvard University]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{NoteFoot|30em}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em|refs=\n\n{{refn|name=days|{{cite journal\n|title=Harvard Commencement Days 1642{{ndash}}1916|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UbkMAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA378|year=1917|pages=309{{ndash}}84\n|work=Publications of the Colonial Society of Massachusetts|last=Matthews|first=Albert\n}} {{open access}} }}\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.harvard.edu/on-campus/commencement Harvard commencement day website]\n\n{{Harvard|state=collapsed}}\n\n[[Category:Harvard University]]\n[[Category:Harvard University-related lists|Commencement speakers]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Meryl streep harvard commencement 2010.JPG|thumb|right|upright=1|[[Meryl Streep]], [[List of honorary degrees|Hon. D.A.]] 2010{{refn\n|{{cite news\n|url=http://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2010/05/honorary-degrees/\n|title=Honorary degrees awarded|date=May 27, 2010 |work=Harvard Gazette\n}} }} ]]\n\n[[File:Harvard Commencement 1911.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1|(l-r) US Navy Secretary (and [[Harvard Board of Overseers|Har{{shy}}vard Over{{shy}}seer]]) [[George von Lengerke Meyer|George Meyer]]; Prof. [[Frank William Taussig|Frank W. Taussig]]; Pres. [[Charles W. Eliot|Eliot]] (who dis{{shy}}dained aca{{shy}}dem{{shy}}ic regal{{shy}}ia);{{refn\n|{{cite web\n|last=Boatner|first=E.B.|title=Pumps and Circumstance: A Guide to Academic Garb\n|url=http://www.harvard.edu/guide-to-academic-garb|publisher=Harvard University\n|accessdate=November 25, 2013\n}} }}\nBishop (and Over{{shy}}seer) [[William Lawrence (bishop)|William Lawrence]] (1911)]]\n\nWhat was originally called ''{{sic|hide=y|[[Harvard College|Harvard\n<!--DO NOT \"FIX\" THIS ORIGINAL SPELLING>>-->Colledge]]}}''<!--<<DO NOT \"FIX\" THIS ORIGINAL SPELLING-->\n(around which [[Harvard University]] eventually grew) held its first [[graduation|Commence{{shy}}ment]] in September 1642, when nine degrees were conferred.{{refn\n| name=spirit |{{cite news\n|url=http://www.harvard.edu/spirit-commencement|title=The Spirit & Spectacle of Harvard Commence{{shy}}ment\n|publisher=Harvard University|last=Hightower|first=Marvin}}{{nbsp}}{{open access}}<!--this may or may not have originally been a Gazette/HMag piece-->\n}}\nToday some 1700 under{{shy}}grad{{shy}}uate degrees, and 5000 advanced degrees from the university's various graduate and professional schools, are conferred each Commence{{shy}}ment Day.<!--extension?-->\n\nEach degree candidate attends three ceremonies: the Morning Exercises, at which degrees are conferred verbally ''en masse''; a smaller midday ceremony (at the candidate's professional or graduate school, or undergraduate House) at which diplomas are given in hand; and, in the afternoon, the annual meeting of the Harvard Alumni Association, at which Harvard's President and the day's featured speaker deliver their addresses.{{refn\n|name=morning_exercises|{{cite web|url=http://commencement.harvard.edu/morning-exercises|year=2013|title=Morning Exercises|publisher=Harvard University Commence{{shy}}ment Office}}{{nbsp}}{{open access}} \n}}\n\nSeveral hundred{{clarify|date=October 2013}} Harvard [[honorary degree]]s (which with few exceptions must be accepted in person) have been awarded since the first was bestowed on [[Benjamin Franklin]] in 1753.{{refn\n|name=honorary|{{cite web\n|title=Honorary Degrees|url=http://www.harvard.edu/honorary-degrees\n|publisher=Harvard University|accessdate=October 1, 2013\n}} }}\nIn 1935 playwright [[George Bernard Shaw]] declined nomination for a Harvard honorary degree, urging instead that Harvard celebrate its three-hundredth anniversary by \"burning itself to the ground{{nbsp}}... as an example to all the other famous old corrupters of youth\" such as [[Yale]].\n\nThe ceremonies shifted from late summer to late June in the nineteenth century,{{NoteTag\n|{{r|days}}{{r|spirit}}\n\"The first Commencement took place in 1642,\" noted Harvard's Commencement director in 2007. \"The difference between 365 years and 356 commencements is accounted for by wars and plagues that cancelled the event.\"{{px1}}{{r|feasting}}\n}}\nand are now held at the end of May.{{Citation needed|date=April 2016}}\nA number of unusual traditions have attached to them over the centuries, including the arrival of certain dignitaries on horseback, occupancy by Harvard's president of the '''Holyoke Chair''' (a \"bizarre\" sixteenth-century contraption prone to tipping over) and the welcoming of newly minted [[bachelor's degree|bachelors]] to \"the fellowship of educated men and women.\"\n\n==Daybreak rituals==\n\n[[File:Harvard University graduation seating, stage perspective.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.6|Seating for degree candidates in [[Tercentenary Theatre (Harvard University)|Tercentenary Theatre]], with banners displaying arms of the various graduate and professional schools, and upperclass houses. Beyond the trees are the columns of [[Widener Library]].]]\n\nMost [[Harvard College#House system|upperclass Houses]] have preliminary rituals of their own. At [[Lowell House]], for example, a perambulating bagpiper alerts seniors at 6:15{{nbsp}}am for a 6:30 breakfast in the House dining hall with members of the [[Senior Common Room]], after which all process (along with members of [[Eliot House]], who have been similarly roused) to [[Memorial Church of Harvard University|Memorial Church]] for a chapel service at 7:45.{{refn\n|{{cite web|url=http://www.lowell.harvard.edu/icb/icb.do?keyword=k69091&pageid=icb.page497528|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130914022344/http://www.lowell.harvard.edu/icb/icb.do?keyword=k69091&pageid=icb.page497528|url-status=dead|archive-date=2013-09-14|title=Yard Ceremony|publisher=Lowell House}} }}{{refn\n|name=moments|{{cite news\n|url=http://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2011/05/moments-that-make-commencement\n|title=Moments that make Commence{{shy}}ment|work=Harvard Gazette|date=May 26, 2011 |first1=Corydon|last1=Ireland|first2=Katie|last2=Koch|first3=Colleen|last3=Walsh\n}} }}\n\n==Morning Exercises==\n\nMorning Exercises are held in the central green of Harvard Yard (known as [[Harvard Yard#Tercentenary Theater|Tercentenary Theatre<!--<<do not \"Americanize\" this spelling-->]]);{{r|morning_exercises}}<!--explain naming of Terc Th--> the dais is before the steps of [[Memorial Church of Harvard University|Memorial Church]], facing [[Widener Library]].{{NoteTag\n|{{refn\n|{{cite web\n|url=http://commencement.harvard.edu/locations-maps-and-directions\n|title=2013 Commencement Seating, Tercentenary Theater, Morning Exercises\n|publisher=Harvard University Commence{{shy}}ment Office |accessdate=October 10, 2013\n}} }}\nDegree-granting exercises were held in [[Sanders Theatre]] from the late nineteenth century through the early twentieth centuries, and prior to that in a succession of locations.{{clarify|date=May 2014}}{{citation needed|date=May 2014}}\n}}\nSome 32,000 people attend the event, including university officials, civic dignitaries, faculty, honorees, alumni, family and guests. Degree candidates wear cap and gown or other academic regalia (see [[Academic regalia of Harvard University]]).{{refn\n|name=grad_and_prof|{{cite web\n|title=Graduate and Professional Schools\n|url=http://commencement.harvard.edu/graduate-and-professional-schools\n|publisher=Harvard University Commence{{shy}}ment Office\n}} }}\n\n===Academic Parade===\n\n{{nobr|The first to enter are candidates for}}<!--<<nobr forces text below img when window is narrow--> graduate and professional degrees, followed by alumni and alumnae.\nCandidates for under{{shy}}grad{{shy}}uate degrees enter next, traditionally removing headgear as they pass the [[John Harvard (statue)|John Harvard statue]] en route.{{refn\n|{{cite news\n|last=Callan |first=Richard L. |url=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1984/4/28/100-dears-of-solitude-pthe-john/ |title=100 Dears of Solitude: John Harvard Finishes His First Century |work=Harvard Crimson |date=April 28, 1984}}\n}}{{refn\n|{{cite news\n|url=http://harvardmagazine.com/1999/05/ner.reading.html|title=Reading the Regalia: A guide to deciphering the academic dress code |work=Harvard Magazine |date=May 1999|last=Rose|first=Cynthia\n}} }}\nFinally comes the [[President of Harvard University|Presi{{shy}}dent's]] Procession, as follows:{{r|spirit}}{{refn\n|{{cite web\n|url=http://commencement.harvard.edu/locations-maps-and-directions|year=2013\n|title=Locations, Maps and Directions|publisher=Harvard University Commence{{shy}}ment Office}}{{nbsp}}{{open access}}\n}}\n\n{|<!--<<BEGIN TABLE-->\n|-\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* {{nobr|the [[Sheriff#United States|sheriffs]] of [[Middlesex County, Massachusetts|Middlesex]]}}<!--<<nobr forces text below img when window is narrow--> and [[Suffolk County, Massachusetts|Suffolk]] counties{{NoteTag|name=officials}} (who have earlier entered the Yard{{mdashb}}in [[morning dress|morning coats]], [[top hat]]s, and striped pants with swords and [[scabbard|scab{{shy}}bard]]s{{mdashb}}through the [[Johnston Gate]], riding white horses);{{r|wonderment|feasting}}\n* the [[Harvard University Marshal|University Marshal]],{{NoteTag| \"{{bracket|[[Morris Hicky Morgan]]}} was the first regular University Marshal, with the title of Marshal of Commence{{shy}}ment from 1896 to 1908 and of University Marshal until his death in March 1910. A Chief Marshal had been appointed for the Bicentennial Celebration in 1836 and for the 250th Celebration in 1886. It has not been discovered who ran ordinary academic exercises before 1896; probably an ''ad hoc'' Marshal was appointed,\" wrote Mason Hammond in the ''Harvard Library bulletin.''{{refn\n|name=hammond_officialterms|{{cite news\n|publisher=Harvard University|work=Harvard Library bulletin\n|volume=XXXV |number=3 |date=Summer 1987 |last=Hammond  |first=Mason \n|title=Official Terms in Latin and English for Harvard College or University |pages=294{{ndash}}310 \n}}<!--<<end cite--> }}<!--<<end efn--> }}<!--<<end note--> escorting the Presi{{shy}}dent and any former Harvard presi{{shy}}dents in attendance;\n* the [[President and Fellows of Harvard College|Fellows of Harvard College]];<!--unfortunate that multiple links end up same place e.g. this one, and [[President]]-->\n* the [[Harvard Board of Overseers|Honorable and Rever{{shy}}end the Board of Overseers]];<!--explain history of overseer membership vs Governor etc-->\n* the [[Governor of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts|Governor of the Common{{shy}}wealth of Massa{{shy}}chu{{shy}}setts]]{{NoteTag\n|name=officials<!--<<BEGIN NOTE-->\n|The governor and sheriffs are among several public officials, not otherwise affiliated with Harvard, who have long taken part in the ceremonies.{{clarify|date=October 2013}}{{refn\n|name=colonial|{{cite book\n|work=Publications of the Colonial Society of Massachusetts|volume= XVIII. Transactions 1915{{ndash}}1916|year=1917|issue=April 1916|pages=309{{ndash}}384|title=Harvard Commence{{shy}}ment Days 1642{{ndash}}1916|first=Albert|last=Matthews|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UbkMAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA309#v=onepage&q&f=false\n}}<!--<<end cite-->}}<!--end refn-->\nBy tradition the Middlesex Sheriff closes the ceremony by crying, \"The meeting is adjourned,\" though in 1997 Sheriff [[James DiPaola]], \"in his first Harvard Commence{{shy}}ment and clearly enjoying his role, wanted more lines. At the end he boomed, 'Marshal{{px1}}! As the sheriff of Middlesex County, I have news! The meeting is adjourned{{px1}}!{{px2}}{{'\"}}{{px1}}{{refn\n|{{cite news\n|url=http://harvardmagazine.com/1997/07/commencement-confetti<!-- or http://harvardmagazine.com/1997/07a/jhj.confetti.html-->|work=Harvard Magazine|title=John Harvard's Journal: Commence{{shy}}ment Confetti|date=July{{ndash}}August 1997\n}} }}\n{{paragraph break}}\nNot all outside participants have been wholeheartedly enthusiastic.\nIn the 1930s Governor [[Paul Dever]],{{when|date=July 2014}} to the chagrin of Harvard officials and alumni, shunned the pre{{shy}}scribed morning coat for a regular tuxedo and straw hat, and Governor [[James Michael Curley]]{{when|date=July 2014}} appeared in silk stockings, knee britches, powdered wig, and a [[tricorn hat]] with plume.\n(When challenged by Harvard officials{{mdashb}}\"the story goes\", according to the Harvard ''Crimson''{{mdashb}}Curley produced the Massachusetts Bay Colony's statutes covering Harvard Commence{{shy}}ment dress, and on the basis of its authority claimed to be the only person present who was properly attired.)\n{{paragraph break}}\nIn 1970 Middlesex Sheriff [[John J. Buckley]] objected to the traditional costume he would be required to wear. After Suffolk Sheriff [[Thomas S. Eisenstadt]] was asked to open and close in Buckley's stead, Cambridge mayor [[Alfred Vellucci]] mused, \"Now I see they're going to have Tom Eisenstadt march with the sword. Where is he going to get a sword unless he borrows one from the [[Don Juan Drum and Bugle Corps]]?\"{{px1}}{{refn\n|{{cite news\n|work=Harvard Crimson|title=Sheriff Cops out on Commence{{shy}}ment|date=June 10, 1970\n|last=Epps|first=Garrett|\nurl=http://www.thecrimson.com/article/1970/6/10/sheriff-cops-out-on-commencement-pcommencement\n}} }}\n}}<!--END NOTE--> (who as of 1971 no longer arrives on horseback with armed, mounted escorts);{{NoteTag\n|\"As recently as [[Francis Sargent]]'s 1970 attendance, the Governor of Massachusetts traditionally arrived at Commence{{shy}}ment with 17th-century mounted, scarlet-coated guard, which escorted him from the State House to the Johnston Gate. The guard bore pikes, somewhat less useful today than when Governor [[Thomas Dudley]] rode to the first Commence{{shy}}ment despite warnings of possible ambush by Indians.\"{{px1}}{{r|spirit}}\n}}\n* candidates for [[honorary degree]]s (whose identities are announced only on the day itself) with their faculty escorts;\n* the sundry [[Dean (education)|deans]] and vice-presidents of the university;\n* the [[Faculty (academic staff)|faculty]], according to [[Academic ranks (United States)|rank]];\n| valign=\"top\" |<!-- - - - - COLUMN BREAK - - - - - -->\n* remaining officers of the university;{{clarify|date=October 2013}}\n* former Fellows and Overseers, former faculty, former officers of the alumni/{{zwsp}}alumnae associations;\n* the [[Phi Beta Kappa Society|Phi Beta Kappa]] Presi{{shy}}dent and Orator;\n* the Trustee of [[The Charity of Edward Hopkins]];<!--source says singular Trustee but seems likely s.b. plural-->\n* the {{sic|hide=y|\"teaching elders [ministers] of the sixe [historically] next adjoining townes, that is [[Cambridge, Massachusetts|Cambridge]], [[Watertown, Massachusetts|Water{{shy}}towne]], [[Charlestown, Massachusetts|Char{{shy}}les{{shy}}towne]], [[Boston]], [[Roxbury, Massachusetts|Roxberry]], and [[Dorchester, Massachusetts|Dorches{{shy}}ter]]\"}},{{refn\n|name=charter|{{cite web\n |url         = http://hlcra.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2013/04/harvardcharter.pdf\n |title       = The Charter of the Presi{{shy}}dent and Fellows of Harvard College\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20131012062952/http://hlcra.harvard.edu/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2013/04/harvardcharter.pdf\n |archivedate = 2013-10-12\n}} }}<!--more specific cite, please--> and clergy of the \"Old Cambridge\" churches;{{clarify|date=October 2013}}<!--enumerate, though unclear wheterh the Old Camb clergy are included in the first list already-->\n* consuls to Boston;{{clarify|date=October 2013}}\n* state and federal judges;{{who|date=October 2013}}\n* past recipients of honorary degrees;\n* public officials;{{clarify|date=October 2013}}\n* other guests.{{clarify|date=October 2013}}\n|}<!--<<END TABLE-->\n{{anchor|holyoke_chair_description}}\n\n===Holyoke Chair===\n[[File:HarvardUniversityPresident'sChair QuincySketch.gif|thumb|left|upright=0.8|The \"bizarre\" Holyoke Chair, reserved for Harvard's president]]\n\n{{Quote box\n |quote  = At Cambridge. Is kept in the College there.<br/>Seems but little the worse for wear.\n<br/>That's remarkable when I say<br/>It was old in [[Edward Holyoke|President Holyoke's]] day.\n |source = [[Oliver Wendell Holmes, Sr.|Oliver Wendell Holmes]]<br/>\"Facts respecting an old arm-chair\"<br/>''[[The Autocrat of the Breakfast-Table]]''{{r|chair-gazette}}\n |width  = 21em |align  = right |salign=right\n}}\n\n{{nobr|On the dais the Presi}}{{shy}}dent occupies the Holyoke Chair, an uncom{{shy}}fort{{shy}}able{{r|feasting}} and {{shy|treach|er|ous}} [[Elizabethan and Jacobean furniture|Elizabethan]] [[turned chair]] reserved for such ceremonies since at least 1770 (when it was already some two hundred years old).\nCalled \"bizarre{{nbsp}}... with a complex frame and top-heavy superstructure\", its \"square framework set on the single rear post makes [it] tip over easily to either side.\"{{px1}}{{refn\n|name=trent|{{cite book|last1=Fairbanks|first1=Jonathan L|last2=Trent|first2=Robert|publisher=Museum of Fine Arts, Boston. Department of American Decorative Arts and Sculpture |year=1982|volume=3|page=512|title=New England Begins: The Seven{{shy}}teenth Century\n}} }}\nSaid the ''Harvard Gazette'' in 2007, \"When the chair holds its robed occupant, onlookers cannot detect the odd geometry by which its triangular seat points toward a square back rippling with knobby dowels and finials. Perhaps by striking their own precarious balance in this strange seat of authority, the successors of [[Edward Holyoke]] [Harvard's president 1737{{ndash}}69] come to sense what the job is all about.\"{{px1}}{{NoteTag\n|{{refn |name=chair-gazette|{{cite news\n|url=http://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2007/09/the-presidents-chair\n|title=The Presi{{shy}}dent's Chair|date=September 24, 2007| last=Hightower|first=Marvin | work=Harvard Gazette}}{{nbsp}}{{open access}}\n}}\nMeasuring 46.5 in (118 cm) high and 32.5 in (83 cm) wide, its seat about 20 inches (51 cm) from the floor and about as deep, the Holyoke Chair is thought to have been made in England or Wales between 1550 and 1600.{{r|trent}} \"[A] display of virtuoso [[wikt:turning#English-shaping|turning]],\" it was bought for Harvard by Holyoke, who saw it as \"suitable to the authority of the presi{{shy}}dent and establishing an iconographic link between Harvard College and its late-medieval English prototypes, Oxford and Cambridge,\" in the words of Jonathan Fairbanks and Robert Trent.\nAlthough the \"thronelike quality [lends] an official air, [chairs of this design] were undoubtedly domestic chairs originally\",{{r|trent}}\nand indeed (according to a 1903 ''New York Times'' article) its use by Holyoke was at first \"merely as a serviceable piece of every-day furniture.\"{{px1}}{{refn\n|name=chair-nyt|{{cite news\n|url=https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1903/02/22/101974940.pdf|title=Harvard's Old Colonial Chair {{ndash}} Thirteen Presi{{shy}}dents Have Used It in Turn|work=New York Times|date=February 22, 1903}}{{nbsp}}{{open access}}\n}}\n{{paragraph break}}\nEven after its first recorded ceremonial use (at the 1770 installation of Presi{{shy}}dent [[Samuel Locke]]) the Presi{{shy}}dent's Chair \"used to stand in the Harvard library {{bracket|[[Gore Hall]]}}, where, according to tradition, it gave a student the right to kiss any young woman whom he was showing through the college and who throughtlessly sat down on it. Whether or not the privilege was often or ever taken advantage of the present generation has no means of knowing.\"{{px1}}{{r|chair-nyt}}\nThe [[Fogg Museum]] now has custody between ceremonial uses.{{r|chair-gazette}}\n}}\n{{clear left}}\n\n===Ceremonies===\n\n[[File:Oppenheimer Marshall Conant Bradley and others at Harvard.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.8|1947 honorands: [[J. Robert Oppenheimer|J.{{nbsp}}Robert Oppen{{shy}}heim{{shy}}er]] (left), [[George C. Marshall|George C. Mar{{shy}}shall]] (third left, speak{{shy}}ing with Pres. [[James B. Conant]]), [[Omar N. Bradley]] (third right), [[T. S. Eliot|T.{{nbsp}}S. Eliot]] (2nd right).]]\n\nAt the University Marshal's call (\"Mister Sheriff, pray give us order\") the Middlesex Sheriff takes to the dais, strikes it thrice with the butt of his staff, and intones, \"The meeting will be in order.\"{{px1}}{{refn|\nname=feasting|{{cite news\n|url=http://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2007/05/commencement-feasting-customs-color-date-to-medieval-europe\n|title=Commencement feasting, customs, color date to medieval Europe | last=Cromie | first =William J. | date=May 31, 2007 |work=Harvard Gazette}}{{nbsp}}{{open access}}\n}}\nThree student speakers (Under{{shy}}grad{{shy}}uate English, Under{{shy}}grad{{shy}}uate Latin, and Graduate English) are introduced and deliver their addresses.{{clarify|date=October 2013}}<!--<<selected how etc-->\n\nThen, according to the order in which the various graduate and professional schools were created,{{citation needed|date=October 2013}} the dean of each school steps forward to present, ''en masse,'' that school's degree candidates.\nEach group stands for the President's incantation conferring their degrees, which is followed by<!--followed, or preceded?--> a traditional welcome or exhortation:\ndoctoral graduates, for example, are welcomed \"to the ancient and universal company of scholars\", while law graduates are reminded to \"aid in the shaping and application of those wise restraints that make us free.\"\nLast to be graduated are the [[bachelor's degree|Bachelor's]] candidates, who are then welcomed to \"the fellowship of educated men and women.\"{{px1}}{{r|spirit}}<!--<<check this covers order of presentation-->\n\nHonorary degrees are then bestowed.\nFinally, all rise to sing \"The Harvard Hymn\",{{refn\n|{{cite web\n|url=http://www.math.harvard.edu/history/hymn|title=The Harvard Hymn\n|author1=James Bradstreet Greenough|author2=John Knowles Paine}} {{better source<!--math dept isn't the best source-->|date=October 2013}} }}{{refn\n|name=\"Rossano\"|{{cite web\n|url=http://harvardmagazine.com/2000/05/grace-notes.html\n|title=Grace Notes|last=Rossano|first=Cynthia W.|date=May{{ndash}}June 2000\n|publisher=Harvard Magazine}} }}\nexpressing the hope (''Integri sint curatores, Eruditi professores, Largiantur donatores''{{mdashb}}printed\nlyrics are supplied){{refn\n|{{cite news\n|work=Harvard Magazine|title=John Harvard's Journal: Center of Attention|date=July{{ndash}}August 2011 |url=http://harvardmagazine.com/2011/07/center-of-attention\n}} }}\nthat the trustees, faculty and benefactors will manifest (respectively) integrity, wisdom, and generosity.{{r|festival}}\nAfter a benediction is said, the Middlesex Sheriff declares the ceremony closed and the Presi{{shy}}dent's Procession <!--http://commencement.harvard.edu/graduate-and-professional-schools says President's Division--> departs.\n\nOnce the dais is clear the [[Harvard Band]] strikes up and the [[Memorial Church of Harvard University|Memorial Church]] bell commences to peal,{{r|Rossano}} joined by bells throughout Cambridge for most of the following hour.<!--bell rings at ceremony opening as well, but not sure when relative to sheriff etc-->{{NoteTag\n|The other participating bells are those of<!--linking needed!--> [[Lowell House#bells|Lowell House]], the Harvard Business School's [[Baker Hall (Harvard University)|Baker Hall]], [[Christ Church (Cambridge, Massachusetts)|Christ Church Cambridge]], the Harvard Divinity School's [[Andover Hall]], the [[Church of the New Jerusalem (Cambridge, Massachusetts)|Church of the New Jerusalem]],\n[[First Church in Cambridge (Congregational)|First Church Congregational]],<!--some confusion as to which church this actually is-->\nFirst Parish Unitarian Universalist, St.{{nbsp}}Paul Roman Catholic Church, St. {{nbsp}}Peter's Roman Catholic Church, University Lutheran Church, Holy Trinity Armenian Apostolic Church, [[North Prospect United Church of Christ]], and St.{{nbsp}}Anthony's Church.{{refn\n|name=wonderment|{{cite news\n|url=http://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2010/05/commence-wonderment\n|title=Commencement wonderment|date=May 26, 2010 |last=Sweeney|first=Sarah|work=Harvard Gazette}}{{nbsp}}{{open access}}\n}}<!--<<end cite--> }}<!--<<end note-->\n\n{{clear}}\n[[File:HarvardCommencement 1791 Broadside.jpg|thumb|left|upright=1.7|Broadside, in Latin, for 1791 exer{{shy}}cises. \"The Illus{{shy}}tri{{shy}}ous [[John Hancock|John Han{{shy}}cock]], Esq., LL.D., Gover{{shy}}nor; Honor{{shy}}able [[Samuel Adams]], Esq., Vice-Governor{{nbsp}}...\"]]\n[[File:1801 Harvard commencement Hilliard.png|thumb|right|upright=1.4|Order of the Exercises (1801) opening with \"A [[wikt:salutatory#English-address|Saluta{{shy}}tory Oration]] in Latin\"]]\n{{clear}}\n\n==Mid-day ceremonies==\n\n[[File:Memorial Hall, Harvard University, Class Day exercises, seniors entering Sander's Theatre.jpg|upright=1.4|thumb|Seniors entering [[Sanders Theatre]] for Class Day exercises (late 19th or early 20th century)]]\n\nAfter the Morning Exercises, each graduate or professional school, and each upperclass House, holds a smaller ceremony (with luncheon) at which its member-graduates are called forward by name to receive their diplomas in hand.<!--prizes awarded??-->\n\n==Alumni Association meeting and afternoon addresses==\nAt the afternoon meeting of the Harvard Alumni Association, the Presi{{shy}}dent and the Commence{{shy}}ment Day speaker <!--others?-->deliver their addresses.\n\nUS Secretary of State (and former Army general) [[George C. Marshall]]'s 1947 address as Commence{{shy}}ment Day Speaker famously outlined a plan (soon known as the [[Marshall Plan]], and for which he would later be awarded the [[Nobel Peace Prize]]) for the economic revival of post-World War II Europe.{{refn\n|name=hmag_marshall|{{cite news\n|url=http://harvardmagazine.com/1997/05/marshall.html|title=The Ultimate Commence{{shy}}ment Address: The Making of George C. Marshall's \"routine\" speech\"|date=May 1997|work=Harvard Magazine|first=John T.|last=Bethell\n}} }}\n\n==Historical notes==\n\n===Sheriffs===\n\n[[File:LioneldeJerseyHarvard HarvardCommencement 1915June.png|thumb|right|upright=1.4|[[Lionel de Jersey Harvard]] ''(r)'' with fellow seniors, 1915]]\n[[File:Harvard Class of 2015 graduates in Harvard Yard.jpg|thumb|right|upright=1.4|Outside [[Sever Gate (Harvard University)|Sever Gate]], 2015 ]]\n\n\"Our fathers{{nbsp}}... closely associated the thirst for learning and that for beer\", a 1924 Harvard history observed,{{r|batchelder}}\nso that (a modern survey continued) the sheriffs' presence at Commencements \"has a practical origin. Feasting, drinking, and merry{{shy}}making at earlier commence{{shy}}ments often got out of hand. Fights were not unheard of\",\nand commencements in various years have featured two-headed calves, an elephant, and Indians-versus-scholars archery competitions.{{r|feasting}}\nSuch goings-on were sufficiently common knowledge that in 1749, Bostonian [[William Douglass (physician)|William Douglass]] explained to a general readership that the [[Siege of Louisbourg (1745)|siege and capture of Louisbourg]] had been \"carried on in a [[wikt:tumultuary#English-disordered|tumultuary]] random Manner, and resembled a Cambridge Commence{{shy}}ment.\"{{px1}}{{refn\n|name=batchelder|{{cite journal\n|work=The Harvard Graduates' Magazine|title='The Student in Arms'{{mdashb}}Old Style\n|first=Samuel F.|last=Batchelder|volume=XXIX|issue=cxvi|date=June 1921\n|pages=549{{ndash}}571,{{zwsp}}551\n|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1CxYAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA551&lpg=PA551\n}} }}\nThus in 1781, {{quote|{{sic|hide=y|For the prevention of Disorders on Commence{{shy}}ment day, [the Corporation] voted that the Honble [[Henry Gardner Esq]]:<!--apparently https://books.google.com/books?id=m74TAAAAYAAJ&lpg=PA652&pg=PA660 (but there was a son and grandson all of same name--> and the Honble [[Abraham Fuller]] Esq:<!--apparently https://books.google.com/books?id=Aj4VAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA3-PA71--> Justices of the Peace thro' the State, and [[Loammi Baldwin|Loammi Baldwin Esq]]: Sheriff of the County of Middlesex, be requested to give their attendance on that day{{nbsp}}...<!--,{{nbsp}}& to pass the following night at Cambridge; and be informed that suitable lodgings will be provided for them.-->}}{{r|colonial}}\n}}<!--<<end quote-->\nEarlier measures had included the 1693 banning of [[rum cake|plum cake]]{{mdashb}}the enjoyment of which, officials asserted, was unknown at other universities, \"dishonourable to ye Colledge, not gratefull to Wise men, and chargable to [i.e. the fault of] ye Parents\".\nThis was one of many efforts by [[Increase Mather]] (Harvard's president from 1692 to 1701) toward \"<!--I endeavoured the -->Reformation of those excesses{{nbsp}}... [of] Commence{{shy}}ment day and {{sic|weeke at the Colledge,}} so that I might [prevent] disorder and profaneness\"{{px1}}{{r|spirit}}{{mdashb}}for Harvard officials a recurring headache.{{NoteTag\n|{{sic|<!--to prevent spell-correction of this entire note-->\n<!--On April 4, -->In 1721, \"For the preventing Extravagencies at Commencemts. {{bracket|[[Harvard Corporation|The Corporation]] voted}}\n1.{{nbsp}}That the Order{{nbsp}}... phibiting any Scholar to have Plum-cake{{nbsp}}&c in his Study or Chamber [at]<!--check source--> Commence{{shy}}ment be strictly observed.\n2.{{nbsp}}That all mix'd drink make with distill'd Spts be also phibited{{nbsp}}...\n3.{{nbsp}}That the Presidt and Fellows be desired to exhort{{nbsp}}& direct the Scholars to be more moderate and frugall in the Entertainmts.\n4.{{nbsp}}And that the publick dinner usual on the day after Commencmt be lessen'd or laid aside, as the Presidt and Fellows of the House [i.e. the Tutors]{{clarify|date=January 2014}} shall think most convenient.\"\n|hide=y}}\n{{paragraph break}}\nIn 1722, the Corporation \"took more stringent action still\": \"Whereas the Countrey in general and the College in Particular have bin under Such Circumstances, as call aloud for Humiliation, and all due manifestations of it; and that a Suitable retrenchmt of every thing that has the face of Exorbitance or [extravegence] in Expences, especially at Commencmt out to be endeavrd. And Whereas the preparations{{nbsp}}& pvisions that have bin wont to be made at those ties have bin the Occasion of no Small disorders; It is Agreed, and Voted, That henceforth no preparation nor Provision either of Plumb-Cake or rosted, boiled or baked Meats{{nbsp}}& Pyes of any kind shalbe made by any Commencer, nore shal any such have any distilled Liquors, or any Composition made therewth.\"\n{{paragraph break}}\n\"These regulations proving ineffectual,\" in 1726 the Corporation, \"having now had some Discourse about the great Disorders{{nbsp}}& Immoralities yt have attended ye Publick Commence{{shy}}ments; it is agreed yt ye Several Members of ye Corporation will Jndeavour to think of wt may be a proper method for ye preventing of such Disorders{{nbsp}}& Immoralities{{nbsp}}...\"{{px1}}{{r|colonial}}\n}}<!--<<end \"sic\"--><!--and so, what did they think of???--><!--<<END NOTE-->\n\n===Sartorial regulations===\n\nTo curb unseemly [[wikt:sartorial#English-quality of clothes|sartorial]] displays of wealth and social status{{clarify|date=October 2013}} the 1807 Laws of Harvard College provided that, on Commence{{shy}}ment day,{{quote|<!--Candidate for either Degree shall attend the public procession, on Commence{{shy}}ment Day, to and from the College. And every-->[E]very Candidate for a first degree shall be clothed in a black gown, or in a coat of blue grey, a dark blue, or a black color; and no one shall wear any silk nightgown, on said day, nor any gold or silver lace, cord, or edging upon his hat, waistcoat, or any other part of his clothing, in the College, or town of Cambridge.<!-- And any Candidate for his Degree, who shall neglect such attendance, without sufficient reason, to be allowed by the President, or shall be habited contrary to this regulation, shall not be admitted to his Degree that year.-->{{refn|name=festival\n|{{cite journal|url=http://harvardmagazine.com/1997/05/ner.rituals.html|work=Harvard Magazine|date=May 1997|first=Cynthia |last=Rossano|title=These Festival Rites}}{{nbsp}}{{open access}}<!--<<add purpose--><!--<<close cite-->\n}}<!--<<close refn--> }}<!--<<close quote-->\n\n=== George Bernard Shaw ===\n\nResponding to the prospect of being nominated for an honorary degree on the occasion of [[Harvard's Tercentenary celebration]]  in 1936, [[George Bernard Shaw]] wrote: {{quote|Dear Sir, I have to thank you for your proposal to present me as a candidate for an honorary degree of D.L.{{clarify|date=October 2013}} of Harvard University at its tri-centenary celebration. But I cannot pretend that it would be fair for me to accept university degrees when every public reference of mine to our educational system, and especially to the influence of the universities on it, is fiercely hostile. If Harvard would celebrate its three hundredth anniversary by burning itself to the ground and sowing its site with salt, the ceremony would give me the greatest satisfaction as an example to all the other famous old corrupters of youth, including [[Yale]], [[Oxford University|Oxford]], [[Cambridge University|Cambridge]], [[University of Paris|the Sorbonne]], etc. Under these circumstances I should let you down very heavily if you undertook to sponsor me.}} A handwritten postscript read: \"I appreciate the friendliness of your attitude.\"{{px1}}{{refn\n|{{cite book\n|page=[https://archive.org/details/harvardobservedi00beth/page/127 127]|title=Harvard Observed: An Illustrated History of the University in the Twentieth Century|first=John T.|last=Bethell|year=1998|publisher=Harvard University Press|url=https://archive.org/details/harvardobservedi00beth|url-access=registration|quote=shaw salt.|isbn=9780674377332}}\n}}\n\n== <span id=\"speakers\"></span>Commencement speakers ==\n{{incomplete list|date=January 2019}}\n{{columns-list|colwidth=31em|1=\n* 2019: [[Angela Merkel]], [[Chancellor of Germany]] \u2013 ([https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=9ofED6BInFs video])\n* 2018: [[John Lewis (civil rights leader)]]\n* 2017: [[Mark Zuckerberg]], founder of [[Facebook]]\n* 2016: [[Steven Spielberg]], film director, producer, and screenwriter \u2013 ([https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=TYtoDunfu00&index=1&list=PL309451B70B1DE1FF video]; [https://www.entrepreneur.com/article/276561 text])\n* 2015: [[Deval Patrick]], 71st [[Governor of Massachusetts]] \u2013 ([https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-flgIKTSIas video])\n* 2014: [[Michael Bloomberg]], businessman and philanthropist, former [[Mayor of New York City]] \u2013 ([https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zhfn2zgFFJ8 video]; [https://soundcloud.com/harvard/former-nyc-mayor-michael audio]; [https://www.mikebloomberg.com/news/mike-bloomberg-delivers-remarks-at-harvard-universitys-363rd-commencement-ceremony/ text])\n* 2013: [[Oprah Winfrey]], businesswoman and talk show host \u2013 ([http://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/multimedia/oprah-winfrey-commencement-speech-harvard-commencement-2013/ video]; [https://soundcloud.com/harvard/oprah-winfrey-harvard-commencement audio]; [http://news.harvard.edu/gazette/story/2013/05/winfreys-commencement-address/ text])\n* 2012: [[Fareed Zakaria]], journalist, author, former [[Time (magazine)|''TIME'']] editor \u2013 (\"We Live in an Age of Progress\" [http://news.harvard.edu/