ates and brought about the [[American Civil War]].\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Winner (nationally)\n! Votes\n! Percent\n! Loser (nationally)\n! Votes\n! Percent\n! Loser (nationally)\n! Votes\n! Percent\n! Loser (nationally)\n! Votes\n! Percent\n! Electoral<br>Votes\n|-\n| style\"text-align:left\" | [[1860 United States presidential election in Texas|1860]]\n| [[Abraham Lincoln]]\n| no ballots\n| \n| [[Stephen A. Douglas]]\n| 18\n| 0.0\n| '''[[John C. Breckinridge]]'''\n| 47,454\n| 75.5\n| [[John Bell (Tennessee politician)|John Bell]]\n| 15,383\n| 24.5\n| 4\n|}\n\n== Elections prior to 1860 ==\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Winner (nationally)\n! Votes\n! Percent\n! Loser (nationally)\n! Votes\n! Percent\n! Other national<br>candidates{{efn|name=\"national\"}}\n! Votes\n! Percent\n! Electoral<br>Votes\n! Notes\n|-\n| [[1856 United States presidential election in Texas|1856]] || '''[[James Buchanan]]''' || 31,169 || 66.59 || [[John C. Fr\u00e9mont]] || no ballots || || [[Millard Fillmore]] || 15,639 || 33.41 || 4 || \n|-\n| [[1852 United States presidential election in Texas|1852]] || '''[[Franklin Pierce]]''' || 13,552 || 73.07 || [[Winfield Scott]] || 4,995 || 26.93 || [[John P. Hale]] || no ballots || || 4 || \n|-\n| [[1848 United States presidential election in Texas|1848]] || [[Zachary Taylor]] || 4,509 || 29.71 || '''[[Lewis Cass]]''' || 10,668 || 70.29 || [[Martin Van Buren]] || no ballots || || 4 || \n|}\n\n==Notes==\n{{notelist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{United States presidential elections}}\n\n[[Category:United States presidential elections in Texas| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox elections by state\n| state = Texas\n| number_of_elections = 41\n| voted_democrat = 27\n| voted_republican = 14\n| voted_other = 0\n| voted_winning = 25\n| voted_losing = 16\n}}\t\nFollowing is a table of '''United States presidential elections in Texas''', ordered by year. Since its admission to statehood in 1845, [[Texas]] has participated in every U.S. presidential election except the election of 1864 during the [[American Civil War]], when the state had seceded to join the Confederacy, and the election of 1868, when the state was undergoing [[Reconstruction era|Reconstruction]].\n\nIn its first century Texas was a Democratic bastion, only voting for another party once \u2013 in 1928 when anti-Catholic sentiment against Al Smith drove voters to Republican Herbert Hoover. A gradual trend towards increasing social liberalism in the Democratic Party, however, has turned the state (apart from Hispanic [[South Texas]], the [[Trans-Pecos]] and several large cities) into a Republican stronghold. Since 1980 Texas has voted [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] in every election.\n\nWinners of the state are in '''bold'''.\n\n==Elections from 1864 to present==\n\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Winner (nationally)\n! Votes\n! Percent\n! Loser (nationally)\n! Votes\n! Percent\n! Other national<br>candidates{{efn|name=\"national\"|For purposes of these lists, other national candidates are defined as those who won at least one electoral vote, or won at least ten percent of the vote in multiple states.}}\n! Votes\n! Percent\n! Electoral<br>Votes\n! Notes\n|-\n| [[2016 United States presidential election in Texas|2016]] || '''[[Donald Trump]]'''<ref name=\"PV\">[[United States presidential elections in which the winner lost the popular vote|Won the electoral college while losing the popular vote]].</ref> || 4,685,047 || 52.10 || [[Hillary Clinton]] || 3,877,868 || 43.12 ||\u2014\n|  || || 38 || Two faithless electors, one voting for [[John Kasich]], another for [[Ron Paul]].\n|-\n| [[2012 United States presidential election in Texas|2012]] || [[Barack Obama]] || 3,308,124 || 41.38 || '''[[Mitt Romney]]''' || 4,569,843 || 57.17 ||\u2014\n|  || || 38 || \n|-\n| [[2008 United States presidential election in Texas|2008]] || [[Barack Obama]] || 3,528,633 || 43.68 || '''[[John McCai